findings.title: Upgradeability Issues
findings.description: The contract is upgradable but does not follow the upgradability best practices by not adding a gap in the contract storage. This may lead to contract storage layout corruption during an upgrade. The contract inherits EIP712Upgradeable that contains a __gap variable, but it is a best practice to create a new __gap variable that will be more accessible due to variables order.

findings.title: Unsafe Approval
findings.description: The contract MainnetRFQ uses the approve() function inside of the _executeSwap(), which does not update the allowance, but replaces it. This creates a problem when a taker, which is a smart-contract, makes several swaps, and does not withdraw the previous approval.

findings.title: EIP Standard Violation: Missing Value Check
findings.description: According to the EIP-1271 implementation, the s value in the signature verification process should be checked against an upper value. The function _recoverSigner() does not implement an upper bound check for the variable s.

findings.title: Missing Zero Address Validation
findings.description: Address parameters are being used without checking against the possibility of 0x0.

detector.description:
MainnetRFQ.initialize(address)._swapSigner (contracts/MainnetRFQ.sol#81) lacks a zero-check on :
		- swapSigner = _swapSigner (contracts/MainnetRFQ.sol#89)
		- rebalancer = _swapSigner (contracts/MainnetRFQ.sol#90)
Parameter MainnetRFQ.addAdmin(address)._address (contracts/MainnetRFQ.sol#181) is not in mixedCase

findings.title: Missing Array Length Check
findings.description: The function batchClaimBalance() lacks the array length equality checks, which will lead to unexpected behavior if the length of arrays is different.

detector.description: MainnetRFQ.batchClaimBalance(address[],uint256[]) (contracts/MainnetRFQ.sol#279-296) has external calls inside a loop: (success) = address(rebalancer).call{value: _amounts[i]}() (contracts/MainnetRFQ.sol#286)
